te, analyses, comparatively-evaluate any philosophy of any individua=\r\nl is not that difficult and is a valid rational process. \n\nWhile future is =\r\nalways uncertain, but chances look remote for me that I would find Mayavada=\r\n more attractive. It was Sri Adi Shankara&#39;s Mayavada - as is understood and=\r\n propagated by his followers - which I had studied when I was first trying =\r\nto get a grasp of Hindu philosophy. It a nice, compact and easily understan=\r\ndable philosophy. Possibly one the chief reasons why most=C2=A0 intellectua=\r\nls like his Adwaitha apart from being attracted by his personality. It is e=\r\nasier to debate from Sri Shankara&#39;s stand-point. At that time I liked it. L=\r\nater as I got acquainted myself with more varieties of Hindu philosophy, I =\r\nfound others more comprehensive and covering more essential points and usin=\r\ng a very, if I may use this phrase, a bottom-up approach to understanding r=\r\neality, while Sri Shankara&#39;s philosophy is a very top-down approach, with a=\r\n greater thrust on the top and an indeterminate leftover in the bottom. Sha=\r\nnkara&#39;s Adwaitha, Ramanujacharya&#39;s Visistha-adwaitha,\n Vallavacharya&#39;s Sudd=\r\nha Adwaitha - so many varieties of philosophy.\n\nI have a personal view abou=\r\nt judging philosophy. For everything that one giant has said, there is alwa=\r\nys another one who has said exactly the opposite. And a third and forth one=\r\n who came up with a different view-point, differing with all the previous o=\r\nnes. And each of these giants have spoken with the utmost conviction of the=\r\nir own realizations of truths. So personality and stature of the philosophe=\r\nr should play no role in an objective analysis of the philosophy. Just like=\r\n the personality and stature of a mathematician is of no use in=C2=A0 judgi=\r\nng the correctness of a mathematical theory.=C2=A0 Spiritually, the reality=\r\n is same (and it maybe a very complex reality). But philosophically each ha=\r\nve differences which cannot the ignored. In such an intellectual climate, i=\r\nn my personal opinion, it is fair enough to discard one philosophy for anot=\r\nher, after a thorough and detailed contemplation of the pros and cons.\n\nFro=\r\nm a spiritual view-point all this is utterly meaningless. Which ever spirit=\r\nual giant one chooses to hang on to, if sincere faith, reverence and effort=\r\n is engaged, surely progress will happen in time. But philosophy is a anoth=\r\ner matter.\n\n[To make my stand clearer, let me say hypothetically that IF by=\r\n some strange miracle of God, Sri Adi Shankara were to come and stand infor=\r\nnt of me, I would have no qualms about falling at his feet and bowing down =\r\nto him and asking for his blessings, for his spiritual stature is unquestio=\r\nnable. Yet I will still not be agreeable to the philosophy he propagated du=\r\nring the time he lived.]\n\n-Best Regards\n=C2=A0Rajarshi\n\n\n\nawaktam wyaktimAp=\r\nannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah |\nparam bhAwamajAnanto mamAwyayamanuttamam ||[=\r\n7:24]\n\n\n________________________________\n From: vedic_pathak &lt;vedic_pathak@=\r\nyahoo.com&gt;\nTo: vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com \nSent: Thursday, 11 October 201=\r\n2 10:32 PM\nSubject: [vedic-wisdom] Re: A thought\n \n\n=C2=A0 \nDear Rajarshi,\n=\r\n\n&gt;&gt;&gt;Yet, I have equally no qualms in rejecting his philosophy&lt;&lt;&lt;\n\nactually =\r\n&quot;rejecting&quot; may not be the right word you probably mistakenly used. It coul=\r\nd be that it does not attract you that much incomparision to the other one =\r\nand/or as in case of Aurobindo&#39;s philosophy which did not make sense earlie=\r\nr and which now makes a lot of sense. same way, it is possible for Adi Shan=\r\nkara&#39;s adwait.\n\nIt may require a LOT to reject philosophy of giant such as =\r\nadi Shankara and yet some one may not be able to reject afterall. That is M=\r\nHO.\n\nBest Regards,\n\nUtpal \n\n--- In vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.c